   The Q stands for Quantity.  A number will be placed below it
   indicating how many of that particular unit they have.  For instance
   Lukas has 6 Archers.

   The T stands for Terrain.  A lengthy description follows:

        Depending upon what terrian you are in, the better (or worse)
        chances you have of staving off an attack.  A players
        terrain will be flashing RED if they are moving.  A moving
        army is a much easier kill.  So kill somebody you see moving.

        Clear Terrain:  Offers NO protection.  Is represented by a '='.
        Woods        :  Offers good protection (-20%) and is represented
                        by a  (alt - 157).  Can be hit by a Tree Burn
                        action.
        Brush        :  Offers decent protection (-10%) and is
                        represented by a B
        Hills        :  Represented by a ï (alt - 239).  This offers
                        minus 10% to defense and adds 10% if you are
                        attcking FROM it!
        Towers       :  Represented by a T.  This offers -30% but
                        is susceptible to an earthquake spell.
        Castles      :  Represented by a C.  This offers -40% but
                        is susceptible to an earthquake spell.
        Swamps       :  Causes the player to suffer with a -10% on
                        attacks as well as defense.  It takes a
                        movement action to get out with no range
                        increment and there is a 50% failure of
                        getting out and the action wasted.  This is
                        represented by a Twisting sideways 8.  You may
                        play a swamp against another play.  Do note,
                        that it is NOT an action to play one on
                        an opponent!


    S column is for Smoke.  If a player is afflicted with smoke his
    column will show an S.  Smoke has the same defensive properties
    as a swamp does but is easy to get out of.  Merely by moving
    (in any direction) and then placing terrain will get rid
    of smoke.

    R Range....  Each player starts out at range 0.  One of the
    objectives to the game is to reach range 5.  A player plays
    movement cards in order to move backwards or forwards or sideways.
    Sideways means just moving from side to side and not into another
    army.  Basically used to switch terrains without advancing.
    No player can get past range 5 or below 0.

    Player's distances can be computed by ADDING the ranges.  Therefore
    Pit Fiend's Archer at Range 0 and a Footmen of Lukas's team at range
    0 are at range 0.  Where if I was at range 3 and his was at 1
    we'd be at RANGE 4.  Do note that a player cannot exceed 5.  Meaning
    that let's say Lukas's Dragon is at Range 3 and my archer is at
    range 2.  We therefore are at range 5.  I CANNOT move my archer
    to range 3 (3+3 > 5) without first KILLING all of Lukas's Dragons.
    If and when I do this, his 0 dragons will be set back to zero.
    A similar situation is above where Raelini's Archers are at
    Range 4 where Lukas's archers at 1.  Raelini cannot move forward
    to win the game until she defeats Lukas's archers or Lukas moves
    his archers back.

