Fire Rules:

      Here is a table showing you some facts about the various
      strengths of the various groups.  This table is considered
      to assume a group of ONE.  Meaning 1 Archer, 1 Footman etc.
    Range  0        1       2       3      4      5     Defense Modification

Archer     1       1.5      2       2      1     0.5      0
Footman   0.5      1        1.25    1.75   2.25   3       8
Wizard     1       2        3       3      1     0.5      16
Knight    0.75     1        2       3      4      5       32
Dragon     5       6        7       8      9     10       48

What does this all mean?  Well it means that if I have 12 Archers
at Range 2 then I can use 24 point in fire power.  Each fire card
has a number on it.  You can use any combination of fire power cards
up to your maximum to fire.  When you hit 'F' you will be prompted with
the following:

  A-F,0 to fire,?:

  By hitting ? you will be asked to find what group you are intending
  to use to fire with.  It will ask you who your target is.  It will
  then compute the maximum firepower that you can muster, it is
  recommended that you do this always to select the best possible
  combination of fire cards.

  By hitting A-F you can select cards.  A number in command line
  will tell you how many points you have selected.  Hit 0 to commence
  the firing.  If you over select firepower it will tell you and
  cancel firing.  If you decide not fire hit 0, it will not charge an
  action and cancel firing.  Remember you can use as many fire cards,
  as you want, so long as you have the group strength to back them up.

  Your fire strength is then multiplied by 10, resulting in a
  percentage.

  The Defense modification is how hard it is too kill someone.
  Meaning a Footmen is easier to kill than a Dragon.  This is inherent.
  It is added in with ANY terrain bonuses you may be receiving.  This
  modification is multiplied by 8, plus an bonuses from terrain, smoke,
  etc to result in a percentage which is subtracted from the attacker's
  percentage.

  Percentages of 0 or less have a 1% chance of killing and percentages
  greater than 99 are 99% effective.

  Once the percentage is computed it then determines how many are killed.
  You will be asked if you like the chances and you may abort the fire
  mission if you do not like the odds without loss of action or cards.
  The results of combat are random, not guarenteed.  So if you have a
  75% of killed each of 4 Knights and only kill 1..... well then that's
  how the cookie crumbles.

  If you kill an entire group their terrain is removed and they are
  sent back to zero range.  Of course, they may get reinforcements later
  and continue along the merry route of winning, but that is hard to
  come by.  You get no extra points for eliminating a person.  When a
  person is Completely eliminated they are not allowed back into the
  game, therefore their army will never regenerate.

  When you call back next day, you will have new cards, depending
  upon what was played and discarded.  There are 184 cards, watch
  for the reportlog to say when it was reshuffled.

  Strategies:
     1)  Use smoke when you want to reduce an opponents archer's
         strength.  Or use them on yourself when you are going
         to be on the "move".

     2)  Use those swamps on an advancing army.  Use them especially
         when you are running low on men and are trying to stave
         off an advancing opponent.

     3)  Remember your race.  Dwarves, don't hestitate to spend
         turns to discard all your cards.  Elves, use those cards,
         and humans discard when you can.  Humans have an advantage
         in the discard department but are the weakest initially.

     4)  Watchout for the elves at the beginning, their archers must
         be stopped.

     5)  Be EXTREMELY fearful of ANYONE no matter what range they
         are at with more than ONE DRAGON.  Three of 'em killed
         practically everyone once.  If you get a Reinforce Dragon
         use it!

     6)  Use the Send Message Commands to work people.  Pick on
         one opponent to get him out of there.  The game becomes
         very long if everybody chips away at everybody else.

     7)  Don't forget you can run SIDEWAYS, advancing into the
         Archer's crosshairs is a deadly thing to attempt.

     8)  Call often and realize which player's don't call a lot.
         There are no bonuses for missing days.  Meaning if no
         one calls in five days you can win by advancing to range
         five.  In other words, there are NO make up turns.  If
         you miss a day, that's your tough.

     9)  Know when to hold them and when to fold em.  Save fire
         cards for moving targets, discard junk cards (extra
         terrain) etc.